    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-07-19T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-07-19T00:00:00-05:00" n="172"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d172">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 711.21/266.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Colombian Minister</gloss>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-07-19">
                            <hi rend="italic">July 19, 1914</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have honor to invite your attention to
                    paragraph five<note n="17" xml:id="d172fn17">Of Article II.</note> of the
                    proposed treaty between the United States and Colombia, which is now pending
                    ratification in the Senate of the United States. It has been brought to my
                    attention that this paragraph five might be interpreted to require the Panama
                    Railroad, in order to transport the specified products of Colombia, to keep the
                    railroad open and retain rolling-stock especially for this purpose, which under
                    the ordinary circumstances of traffic it would not be required to do. As you are
                    aware, Mr. Minister, it was not the intention of the two Governments to impose
                    any burdens of this character on the Panama Railroad; and therefore, in order to
                    prevent the delay which would arise from amending the treaty, I suggest that
                    your Government agree to the interpretation of this paragraph five in the sense
                    which I have indicated above. A note from you to this effect will be
                    sufficient.</p>
                <p>Accept [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">W. J. Bryan</hi>
                    </signed>.</closer>
            </div>
        </body>
